        "title": "Division in Jerusalem — demon, madness, or open eyes?",
        "range": "10:19-21",
        "excerpt": "A division occurred again among the Jews because of these words.",
        "body": "John's three-verse interlude is easy to skip but crucial. The word *schisma* (division) appears for the third time in the Gospel (7:43; 9:16; 10:19), and each time it marks the same pattern: Jesus' words and works split the audience. Some respond with the demonological diagnosis the leaders have leveled before (7:20; 8:48, 52) — *He has a demon and is insane (mainetai); why do you listen to Him?* Others offer the empirical counter-evidence — *these are not the sayings of one demon-possessed. A demon cannot open the eyes of the blind, can he?*\n\nThe second group is explicitly anchored back to chapter 9. The healing of the man born blind is not just narrative background; it is the chapter's piece of forensic evidence. The first group dismisses the discourse on the basis of presumed pathology; the second insists on the integration of word and work. John's whole Gospel argues that the works (*erga*) authenticate the words, and the words interpret the works — and this little parenthesis is the chapter's reminder that the same data produces opposite verdicts depending on the prior disposition of the heart. The leaders have already decided what Jesus must be; their interpretation of His words flows downward from that prior commitment.\n\nThis prepares the reader for the deeper diagnosis Jesus will offer in 10:26 — *you do not believe because you are not of My sheep*. The split in vv. 19-21 is not finally about the quality of the evidence; it is about the orientation of the hearers.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Schisma* (division, v. 19) is the same noun behind English 'schism'; John uses it to mark Christological controversy specifically. *Mainomai* (be insane, v. 20) — the verb behind 'maniac'; the leaders' attempt to medicalize a claim they cannot refute on its merits."
